FAST FACTS:
*1 Year Old - 59 Pounds
*Active, Playful Personality
*Dog Friendly
*Cat Friendly
*Kid Friendly
*Working on Potty & Crate Training
*Training Required

BIO:
Tick-tock, it's time to fill out an adoption application! My name is Tic, and I am a playful young dude who is looking for a lifetime of fun! I'm friendly with everyone I meet: other dogs, cats, and people of all ages. I think it would be a big bonus to have another playful doggie friend in my forever home, and a fenced yard to run around would be awesome, too. I love going for walks - this fluffy stuff my humans tell me is snow is so much fun to bounce through while we stroll the neighborhood! As a younger guy, I would thrive with a family that will help me learn: I am working on potty and crate training, and am eager to start training classes with a family that loves me. I hear training classes are fun, and if you haven't caught on yet, fun is my favorite word! If it is yours, too, I hope you reach out soon!

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS, NO EXCEPTIONS:
*ADOPTION FEE: $300
*Be at least 21 years of age
*Live in a 50-mile radius of Itasca, within the Illinois border
*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household
*Have approval from owner of residence (written in lease)
*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)
*Be approved as a suitable adoptive home by Fetching Tails Foundation
*Be prepared to make a lifetime commitment

If interested please fill out an application on our website at www.fetchingtailsfoundation.org; please make sure you fill in every required field/question or your submission will not go through. Please note that we take time to learn as much as we can about each dog in our care and our bios are our current observations; we are unable to make any guarantees on the future health or temperament of your adopted dog. Most dogs in our care come with unknown pre-rescue history and as such breed and age estimates are an educated guess.

animal.description:
All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, shots current (DHPP, Bordetella and Rabies where applicable), dewormed, flea and tick treated and microchipped.
* If you are interested in a dog, please first read the biography on the dog (keep scrolling down for the bio!) and then go to our website, www.dpsrescue.com for an application. Our adoption fee is $400-$800. Each biography will specifically list the adoption fee.Adoption Fee: $650
Sesame is a 4-5 month old male Beagle-Lab mix who weighs around 12 lbs. We estimate he will probably be in the 25lbs range when full grown. Sesame was a rescue from Korea. The entire litter and Mom were rescued before being sold to the meat market. Sesame is quite the charmer. With his vibrant, playful, and exuberant personality, he is just the pup for someone who wants a fun and affectionate dog to make them laugh.

When Sesame initially meets new people, he is usually very curious and affectionate. He is often very comfortable with people right from the start. Once he gets to know his family, though, his already affectionate personality becomes even more vibrant! While he isn't too much of a cuddler, he is very playful and expressive. He loves chasing and chewing on toys. His fosters like to call him a drama queen because he likes to make his emotions clear. When he is happy, his tail is wagging non-stop. He is also very vocal about his emotions (he likes to talk), but not in an annoying way. Last, he is a bit of a velcro dog. He likes to keep an eye on his humans and will follow people from room to room. He loves to find a nice spot to sunbathe while watching his humans at work or going about their routine.

Sesame is working on some basic training and is excelling quite well! He is very food motivated, and as a result has quickly learned "sit", "down", and "stay". In addition, he is housetrained, crate trained, and walks decently well on the leash. That being said, he could use a bit of training to help him improve his confidence. He spooks easily to loud noises like garbage trucks, cars, loud construction sites, and sometimes other dogs. In order to address this, he will need a bit of training. Finally, because he is still a puppy, he is still teething, but is easily redirected to other toys.

Sesame has established a daily routine with his foster:
"Sesame wakes up little before 8:00 am and goes to a backyard for potty, followed by breakfast, and a quick little walk around a block. Sesame spends the day playing with our dog, Charlie inside and outside, sunbathing, and naps. We all go for a long walk to a park at 5:00 PM followed by dinner. Usually he settles in Charlie's crate around 7:30. They have an indoor wrestling session around 9:00 PM. Last call for potty break around 11:30 then goes to his crate to sleep."

While Sesame is great with humans right from the start, he does take some time to warm up to other animals. When he initially met his (now best friend) foster dog brother he was very nervous and scared, whining and barking to let people know his discomfort. However, once he realized that the dog meant no harm he warmed up. He now likes to follow the dog around from room to room, never letting him out his sight. He also does well with older children, and currently lives with a 14 year old.

Sesame's ideal home will be willing to finish off his training, making sure that he has everything he needs to blossom into a confident adult dog. However, most importantly, Sesame needs a family that will give him all the love and attention he deserves.
Sesame is only an option for those who have had a dog in the last 5 years. If there are children in the home they need to be over the age of 8.

He'd love a family that would like to play with him and go on hikes (when it's warmer!) and then Netflix and chill. He's also a smart boy and is learning commands quickly in his foster home. We require a home visit for each dog we adopt out, so we adopt within a 2 hour radius of Dayton, OH. If you are outside of this radius, we encourage you to contact your local rescue or shelter.

animal.description:
Meet Emmy, a four year old yellow lab. We don't have proof but we are fairly certain she is a purebred. You will always catch Emmy with a toy in her mouth. She LOVES tennis balls! We think toys bring her comfort, as her family just gave her up and her normal is now gone. She was surrendered because her parents are now empty nesters and don't have time for her. We can tell she is scared and confused because she paces the yard outside and tries to dig under the fence to get away. She is dog friendly, but she is so focused on finding her family that she just ignores other dogs while outside. She really needs someone to step up and commit to her forever. You can just see the heartbreak in her eyes when you look at her. She needs to know that not all humans are bad. She is house trained and very well behaved. She needs an owner that will play fetch with her. We think she would enjoy a home where she is the only dog and gets all the attention, at least for a little while. But she could also live with another calm and polite dog. She is medium energy. Enjoys playing with toys but also knows how to relax. She is fully vetted, spayed, and ready to go

Meet 1yr old, 70lb Roddy the german shepherd. He is a gorgeous boy who found himself at high kill central valley shelter. He is smart and sensitive. Poor boy likely lived his life as  a yard dog and lacks life experiences. He is very affectionate and is doing well on house and crate training. He is dog friendly, but awkward and has lots of energy. He would do best with older kids or adult home. He loves water and is full of personality. He loves to go for long walks and is learning leash manners and to calm down a bit. He would greatly benefit from an active home who wanted to train.

Thank you for reading about our awesome dog. All dogs came to us from different situations and we often do not know much about their past, but they are rescue dogs who deserve a second chance and need patience on their journey. All of our dogs our are in foster homes all across the bay area. 

The first step of the process is you must submit an application in order to set up a meet and great or talk with the foster family. Once application is submitted the foster parents will contact you to chat more about the dog and make sure they're a good fit and can answer any further question. The application answers most of all of our questions and can best match you. If you do not get the dog you apply for we can use your same application for 90 days towards another dog in our care and simply forward your app to that foster parent. 
http://form.jotform.com/underdogca/dog-adoption-application

All dogs will be fully vetted (Spay/ Neutered, Micro chipped, DHPP and Rabies Vaccinated) and other possible vet care prior to adoption.

The adoption fee is $350, which is considered a non refundable donation

animal.description:
All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, shots current (DHPP, Bordetella and Rabies where applicable), dewormed, flea and tick treated and microchipped.
* If you are interested in a dog, please first read the biography on the dog (keep scrolling down for the bio!) and then go to our website, www.dpsrescue.com for an application. Our adoption fee is $400-$800. Each biography will specifically list the adoption fee.Adoption Fee: $650
Flo is a 2 year old female Beagle-Dachshund mix who weighs around 17 lbs. This cutie pie is a huge snuggle bug! With her love of naptime, soft blankets, and warm laps, Flo is just the pup for someone who needs a dog to keep them company and love them unconditionally. Flo was originally a rescue from Mexico. She was placed in a home and the home was looking for a dog who was more sedate and showed more deference to their older dogs. She is more of a take charge kinda gal and the two old dogs in the home were left in the dust. The home also felt like she didn't adjust to the colder weather as she would be cold frequently.

Flo tends to be very timid and shy initially with new people, spending most of her time in her crate. But don't worry! Once given a bit of time, Flo will open up and show you her wonderful personality. After spending some time with her foster she now loves to snuggle and sit on the couch. She has also developed a habit of crawling into people's laps and licking their face if they sit on the ground next to her! She is very affectionate to those she loves. In general, Flo's personality is very chill. She is low maintenance and a big couch potato, spending the majority of her day curled up on soft blankets or basking in a sunny spot on the floor.

In between naps, Flo is working on some basic training. She is crate trained and potty trained, and walks very well on the leash. She pulls sometimes but once you stop moving, she will understand that she's supposed to walk by your side. She also loves sniffing around while she is outside but doesn't like particularly long walks. After 20-25 minutes, she wants to go home. She isn't a nuisance barker or digger either. Her only area for improvement is her chewing habits. She loves to dig through the trash and chew up things, so she definitely needs a home that is prepared to address this issue through training and puppy proofing. Last, she will benefit from a home that is willing to provide her with socialization to improve her confidence around new people.

Flo has established a daily routine with her foster:
"Flo wakes up at ~8AM but stays in her crate quietly until her foster parents let her out. They then take her out for a ~20 minute morning walk. After her walk, she is very excited to get fed. The rest of the day Flo is relatively quiet. You'll likely find Flo snuggled up in a comfy spot near people, but not begging for attention. Flo needs to be taken out ~2-3x during the day depending on how much water she drank. In the evening, close to 7PM, Flo is taken out again for a 20-30 minute walk. Most of the day she is just lounging around as she is not a very active dog."

Flo is generally a very sweet dog, but does have her reservations around other animals. She definitely takes her time opening up to other dogs and is often scared of new dogs she meets on walks. That being said, Flo will open up (and even play) with other dogs if she is given time to adjust at her own pace.

Flo is ideal for a home that will give her plenty of time to open up, understanding that she will display her wonderful personality when she is ready. In addition, she will benefit from people that are home often and that are willing to continue her training. However, more than anything else, Flo needs a family to love her unconditionally.

Flo is only an option for those who have had a dog as an adult. If there are children they need to be over the age of 10.
2/2/21 5:36 PM

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

 We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
Bonnie is a delicate, rare treasure! This gentle, timid Italian Greyhound came to PAWS with some serious medical conditions. Because of a painfully-infected mouth and eye, she has recently had many teeth removed and her eye enucleated. However, Bonnie feels like she has a new lease on life! The day after her surgery she was happily snuggling with her human friends and even making some canine acquaintances!

Bonnie does require some unique care: she is very skittish, and though she likes people, she is prone to dart away if she feels startled (which is often). She is not yet housebroken, and when let outside, she must be leashed at all times. Despite her age, she is a fast runner!

Because of her small frame and delicate limbs, Bonnie needs a very gentle forever family. She shouldn't be allowed to attempt to jump down from high (to her) places, and she should only use a plastic crate because of the danger wire crates may pose to her tiny legs. Adorably though, she knows her crate as her ""crib.""

If you think you can provide a safe, gentle home for sweet Bonnie, please reach out to PAWS!

MEET GRACE! 
Little Miss Grace is the only one in the litter of 7 without a family waiting for her. 
Grace is a 10 week old mixed breed puppy that weighs about 11.4 pounds.
From her foster: This girl is a character! She is playful and curious. She adores being with people. She loves cuddling on the couch and doesn’t mind being carried around (though I’m sure that activity will be short lived).  She’s doing great with night time house training and during the day is trained to potty pads. I’m sure she will be relatively easy to house train the rest of the way with individual attention.  Tonight I realized that she has really good focus.  While most of her siblings were distracted and climbing over each other, Grace could stay focused on the treat in my hand.  Such an exciting trait in an almost 10 week old pup!
If you have questions about Grace please  email us at scroungydogs@outlook.com. If you would like to meet Grace please fill out an application at scroungydogs.com.

animal.description:
???Meet Brees!??? 
He’s seeking a long term foster-to-adopt family. Brees is a 2-3 year old neutered male that came from a hoarding case in Louisiana. Brees LOVES other dogs, but kitties not so much. He is house trained and crate trained. He would also do well in a home with older/no children as he has some old injuries we’re dealing with. 
Speaking of which, due to his history Brees comes with a little baggage. He is heart worm positive, but it was caught in the early stages.  Additionally, it was discovered in X-rays that he has an old gunshot wound with the bullet still inside him and a damaged hip. We are awaiting clearance for potential Femoral Head Ostectomy surgery. Hero rescue will support the foster financially through this process. He will require a couple of transports to Towson Vet. 
But don’t let all of that scare you away!! This young man with eyes that can see into your soul has loads of love to give. His injuries don’t slow him down either, even if he probably should ? when he is not playing with any toy he can get his paws on, he’s snuggled up to you as close as he can. He sleeps politely next to me all day while I work. He’s even a little spoiled and sleeps at the foot of the bed, but I think he deserves to be spoiled after how much he’s gone through. Can you add this big handsome hunk to your family and help him through recovery? Be his hero ???? 




 https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/HRMD/Dog

animal.description:
All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, shots current (DHPP, Bordetella and Rabies where applicable), dewormed, flea and tick treated and microchipped.
* If you are interested in a dog, please first read the biography on the dog (keep scrolling down for the bio!) and then go to our website, www.dpsrescue.com for an application. Our adoption fee is $400-$800. Each biography will specifically list the adoption fee.Adoption Fee: $650
Meet Dua! Dua is named after the pop singer Dua Lipa and she is a 1 1/2 - 2 year old Corgi and Jindo mix and hails from Korea! We work with a rescue in Korea that saves dogs from the meat market, meat farms and the local city shelter where few dogs are every adopted. She is currently about 27 lbs, and could not be any sweeter. This good girl doesn't have a mean bone in her body. With her love of nap time and snuggles, Dua is just the pup for a low energy person who wants a companion to keep them company and give them cuddles all day long.

Dua tends to be very shy and timid when meeting new people. But, don't worry! While she may start off this way, she comes out of her shell if given the time. Her foster says that she took 3-4 days to open up. Once she does come out of her shell, Dua transforms into a complete cuddle bug. She now likes to spend her time getting belly rubs from her foster or curling up for naps in her foster's lap. She is a big couch potato! Even better, despite her cuddly nature, she isn't too much of a velcro dog and is capable of spending time entertaining herself. She is perfectly content just being next to you or in your room while you work or sleeping in her crate. On top of her wonderful personality, Dua is very food motivated and is a sucker for treats this comes in handy when gaining her trust and training her.

Speaking of training, Dua is working on some basics with her foster. She is now completely potty trained and has not had a single accident in the house. She walks decently fine on leash but she may pull a bit and zig zag because she loves sniffing and exploring! She does not seem to be reactive to dogs but she may be a bit shy walking or passing by strangers. Lastly, she is not a nuisance barker or whiner and tends not to chew unless you give her something interesting to nibble on. Her only area of improvement is her confidence. She will need continued socialization in order to improve her comfort level with new people.

Dua has also established a daily routine with her foster:
"Her daily routine consists of her waking up around 7am and then we go out for a 45 min-1 hr walk around the neighborhood. After our neighborhood walk, we will feed her around 8am and she has a very good appetite and always finishes her breakfast. From 8am to around noon, she is now content taking a nap or being a couch potato. We will take her out around noon just for a breath of fresh air and a potty break. All afternoon until early evening around 5pm, she continues just to loaf around and nap. Sometimes she will come up to you for belly rubs and kisses. Around 5-6pm, we will take our evening walk around the neighborhood to get some exercise. We will then feed her dinner and she continues to finish her meal. In the evening, she will join us on the couch for some television time and she will curl up against you to make herself comfortable. We will tuck her in around 10:30pm-11pm and she will happily stay in her crate and will sleep through the night."

Dua has done well with the dogs she has met so far. She also lived with multiple dogs in Korea. She is currently living with a dog in her foster home and hasn't had any issues. While she doesn't like to play much (with humans and dogs), she loves to snuggle up with her foster family's husky. Too cute!

Dua is ideal for a home that will give her the space she needs to open up the first few days. She will also benefit from a home that is willing to give her some basic training especially helping her to learn commands like "sit", "down", and "stay". However, more than anything else, Dua needs a home that will give her the unconditional love and attention she deserves.

Dua is only an option for those who have had a dog as an adult. If there are children they need to be over the age of 8.

animal.description:
Hank is a hunk of love looking for his forever home! He is an approximately 16-weeks old retriever/beagle/heeler mix. He currently weighs 27 pounds and will be about 60 lbs when fully grown.  Hank has lots of love to give!

Hank is a typical puppy—adorable and super playful. He loves toys and will play independently or with other dogs. He makes sure to let you know when he wants to play.  Hank really needs an active family and one with another playful dog.  Hank can get nervous when meeting new people so will need a family to reassure him.  He will do best with kids 8 and up. 

He is a very smart boy that will need consistent training to be the best Hank he can be. Hank is doing great with house training but the occasional accident should be expected due to his young age. He sleeps well in his kennel at night but isn’t a very big fan of his kennel during the day. He prefers to be with his people when they are home. He knows “sit” and “down” and is working on mastering “leave it”.  

He would do best in a home with another dog to play with and a fenced-in yard. Hank has been introduced to cats in his foster home. He has not been aggressive towards the cats but does think it’s a fun game to bark at them and get in their space. Hank is looking for a family that will give him lots of ear scratches and playtime. 

Hank is neutered, microchipped, and current on his vaccines.  His adoption fee is $175.

If you would like to adopt Hank and make him a part of your family, please contact ForeverYoursOKC@gmail.com.

animal.description:
This little cutie is Pal.  He is a Border Collie mix, maybe with cattle dog and lab. We are not exactly sure what his DNA says, but we know he is a super cute, loving puppy ready to find his forever home.  At around 13 lbs now, we think Pal will be in the range of 50 lbs when full grown.

Born in early November 2020, Pal is happy, and loves food, playtime and people. He is smart and active, looking for a family that will include him in everything they do.  He will need great socialization to help him grow into a well-mannered adult dog.  Pal is no couch potato – he wants to walk, hike, camp and live an active life!  He will also need opportunities to learn through obedience classes and mental engagement (trick training, games, puzzles).

Pal absolutely needs a canine sibling in his forever home to help build his confidence and model great behavior. Because of his sharp puppy teeth, homes with older kids will be considered. For his safety, we will also prefer homes with physically fenced yards: he is too young for invisible fencing.

Families that work outside the home need to include information in their application about how they will accommodate potty training because Pal may not be left home alone for more than a few hours a day. 

Pal is located in the Minneapolis, MN area. If you think you're a good fit for him, please fill out an application at hoabcr.org/how-to-adopt 

As a foster-based rescue, we do not have a central facility to visit. Meet and greets with specific dogs are arranged once your adoption application (not an inquiry email through Petfinder) has been received, processed, and approved. We are located in Minnesota and adopt to an area 400 miles from Minneapolis/St. Paul.

The adoption fee for puppies is $400 + MN sales tax. This fee includes spay or neuter at the age of 5 months at one of our veterinary clinics. Puppies are up to date on vaccinations at the time of adoption.

animal.description:
Ellie Mae's owner purchased her as a young pup from a breeder to be a guardian on her farm. Ellie Mae had no interest in being a guardian, escaped the barn daily to go roam and visit the neighboring farms. Ellie Mae's owner did not want her to get hit by a car or injured/shot on a neighboring farm. She wanted her to have a family of her own where she could be a companion dog and live her best life so she contacted us. 

Elle Mae is a Great Pyrenees/Aussie mix and we think probably some Husky in her too with that curly tail! Ellie Mae is a very smart girl and a bundle of energy. She LOVES people and other dogs, and is just fine with cats. She has not been around small children. If you love to run, go for hikes or to the lake, Ellie Mae is your girl! She loves water and also loves agility. She had some agility training from her owner. Elie Mae listens well, comes when called and is an affectionate girl. She does well on a leash and is house trained. Ellie Mae will come to you spayed, up to date on vaccinations, up to date on flea/tick preventives, and microchipped. 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved you must pass a home check and a vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. Ellie Mae can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, and Arkansas. We are able to transport Ellie Mae to those states. 

Being fostered in Lawrence, KS
animal.name: Ellie Mae

animal.description:
I am 3 years old, and l am looking for my forever home.

Adoption Donation: $400

All dogs are microchipped, neutered, current on all vaccines, heartworm tested and started on Tri Heart Plus; Vectra 3D.

All household members and any dogs from the household need to be present at the time of the adoption.

Our website is always kept 100% up to date with who is currently available.  As soon as animals are adopted, they are moved to the Adopted Pets page so if they are still listed on the Adoptable Dogs or Cats page, they are still available. So keep any eye on the site for any animals being added as available for adoption as new animals are added everyday! We would recommend if you haven’t done so already that you submit a general online adoption application with us so it is on file for when you are ready to come out and adopt. The adoption counselors will be able to show you many that would be a good fit for your family. Animal House Shelter can not guarantee breed or breed mix of our adoptable animals. The animals are posted on the website as a breed or breed mix based on their physical characteristics they most resemble. We also can not guarantee the ages of our adoptable animals or how large puppies will be when fully grown.

Please fill out an online adoption application. Visit our 'Adopt' page to view adoption process steps, policies, requirements and FAQ. View our 'Visit' page for hours and directions to our shelter. We look forward to seeing you soon!

animal.description:
Meet Max. Max is a senior mini Dachshund who hasn't had the best of care over his lifetime. Max was confiscated by animal control and not returned to the owners. Max had never been neutered (he is neutered now), his skin was in horrible condition, he had horrible ear infections in both ears which have now been treated. Max's skin was in horrible condition because he clearly has allergies that have never been treated or tended to so this has  been going on his whole life. Max has been started on some medications and medicated baths to help with his skin and he is doing much better. This will require attention the  rest of his life, the good thing is he is tiny (he weighs 9.6lbs) so the meds won't cost as much as a large dog.   
Max also has horrible teeth, he likely has never had a dental in his life and his teeth are rotten. We are trying to raise money to have a badly needed dental done on Max, if you would like to donate please contact vegasdobes@aol.com or Brenda at 702-596-9293
Max is a little love bug, he is extremely sweet, he just wants a soft place to spend the rest of his days. 
For more info please visit our website at www.LVDDR.com for info about adoptions and/or email Brenda at vegasdobes@aol.com

Max could really use a sponsor,  if you are interested in sponsoring Max please contact Brenda at 702-596-9293 or  email the address provided,

animal.description: Hi! My name is Toby! I was rescued by an animal shelter in Georgia before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. Prior to my arrival I was living with my previous owner, and lived very happily with his children. The staff here on the ranch like to describe me as a "great big lovable boy! I love to play with other dogs, regardless of their size. While I think I would love to be a part of any family, I would probably be the best fit for a family with older children, as sometimes I am unaware of my size and strength. I am a very big Great Dane who would be thrilled to be matched with an experienced Dane owner who is aware of our unique needs and abilities. Because of my size and energy level, I really do require a big yard to run around in, or maybe even a farm! I'd love a busy lifestyle where I can constantly be involved in the family's activities. I love people, so whether you'd like me to be your official greeter in your home or if you'd like to bring me out and about with you on your daily activities, I'm your guy. I appear to be mostly potty-trained, and always keep my kennel nice and neat. I have also learned to love going on long leashed walks here at the ranch, and I can't wait to start doing the same with you!

animal.description:
PLEASE read his entire bio and answer the questions at the end, we will not respond to you if you don't answer the questions. 

We will process all applications over the next few weeks before reaching out to potential adopters, please only send 1 e-mail with the answers below filled out.

Meet beautiful Greta, she is approx. 3yrs old, spayed female. Greta is a husky mix and 42lbs. Greta has had a journey over the last 3mths, she traveled from a rescue in California to a rescue here in Oregon, she arrived in mid November 2020. Greta was then adopted in early December 2020. Greta ended up at HBPets after she was picked up running loose in Yamhill County. Sadly her new adopter didn't want her back and her Oregon rescue didn't have space for her, so she became an HBPets kid. 

What we have learned about Greta, she is so so sweet, very intelligent, loves activity, eager to please and really just melts your heart. As she is a husky she needs a home with lots of outdoor activity, like hiking, running, agility training. She is young and doesn't want to hang out in a kennel or inside all the time. She would make someone a great running partner. She has been around children 12yrs and older, seems to like other dogs, unsure about cats. 

As with all young Huskies if they are not getting physical activity daily, they will try to escape, they are not meant to be kenneled all day and they do like to chase other animals like squirrels. As with any dog, they should not be allowed off leash until you have a strong bond with them. 


My adoption fee is $225

1. Do you rent or own your home? If you rent can you provide a letter from your landlord stating you can have a large dog. 
2. Do you have a fenced yard? Do you have a large yard? 
3. How many people live in your home and age groups
4. How many animals and types live in your home 
5. Have you had a Husky before? 
6. Our you active outside the home?
7. Do you have time to take her for walks everyday or interact with her? Primary Color: Black Secondary Color: White Weight: 42lbs Age: 3yrs 0mths 0wks Animal has been Spayed

animal.description:
**WE ARE CURRENTLY DOING ADOPTIONS BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. YOU MUST CALL TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING. PLEASE LEAVE US A VOICEMAIL IF YOU ARE UNABLE TO REACH US. THANK YOU FOR YOUR PATIENCE AND UNDERSTANDING.- CCDP STAFF**

Hi there. My name is Alex. I'm about 1-2 years old and I weigh about 50 lbs. 
I was abandoned by my owner, then surrendered to the pound. 
I am a very sweet boy. I am very energetic and would do best in a home where I could get plenty of exercise. 
I love people and I get along well with most other dogs. 
I am very clean in my kennel at night and appear to be housebroken.
If you're looking for a sweet dog to add to your family, please consider adopting me.

Our adoption fee is $150.00. The pound DOES NOT accept checks for adoption fees. We're able to accept cash for adoption OR Visa/ Mastercard/ Discover Card. A convenience fee of 2.39% will be applied to all credit/ debit card adoptions. If you intend to do a foster-to-adopt, the fee must be cash. ALL dogs/puppies adopted from our shelter will receive their parvo distemper vaccine, bordetella vaccine, rabies vaccine (if aged at 12 weeks or older), be dewormed with a 3 day course of panacur dewormer, be microchipped, receive their current Ohio dog license and will be spayed or neutered. ALL DOGS/PUPPIES WILL BE SPAYED OR NEUTERED unless a health issue prohibits the surgery from being performed. Not all dogs posted for adoption are spayed/ neutered yet. If you're driving a long distance to adopt, please verify that the vetting process has been completed and dog you're interested in adopting is still available for adoption. The above mentioned vetting is all included in your adoption fee. The adoption fee and what is included in the adoption fee is NON-NEGOTIABLE.

Adoptions MUST be done at the pound and in person as there is paperwork to fill out and an adoption contract that must be signed by the adopter. This means you must be willing to travel to our shelter to adopt.

IF the dog you're interested in adopting has medical conditions or injuries which require medical treatment, we ask that you help with the medical bills so we can continue to help the dogs coming in who need additional vet care.
We are a county run shelter, therefore we cannot control our intake or the health or behavior of the dogs that come in to our shelter.

Although we try our hardest to place all of our adoptable dogs, there are certain circumstances in which any dog in our care could be euthanized at any time and without further notice (IE: sudden untreatable medical condition or injury, temperament or behavioral problems which may not be apparent when the dog first arrives, lack or space, etc.), therefore all dogs at our shelter should be considered urgent. The adoption of a more highly adoptable dog will mean more time for the less adoptable dog in the kennel next to him!

Shelter hours are: Monday-Friday: 8 am- 4 pm
Saturday: 8 am - 11 am.
Sunday: 8 am - 11 am.
Adoptions are always welcome during hours of operation. We will make special arrangements for adoptions in advance.
There is nobody in the office on Saturday and Sunday, so therefore we are unable to answer or return phone calls over the weekend.

Can't adopt a dog? We would love to have more volunteers who are able to spend time with our dogs! The dogs LOVE going for walks and the socialization and exercise helps make the dogs more adoptable.

Contact information:
8455 County Home Road
Lisbon, OH 44432
(330)424-6663
Email: hpecorelli@ccclerk.org

All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, shots current (DHPP, Bordetella and Rabies where applicable), dewormed, flea and tick treated and microchipped.
* If you are interested in a dog, please first read the biography on the dog (keep scrolling down for the bio!) and then go to our website, www.dpsrescue.com for an application. Our adoption fee is $400-$800. Each biography will specifically list the adoption fee.Adoption Fee: $650
Fern is a 1 year old Dachshund-Beagle mix who weighs 8.7 lbs. She was a rescue from the shelter. She was listed as a stray. This sweet girl is a gem. With her loving, happy, sweet, and playful personality, she has all the best qualities in just the right amounts. She is the perfect pup to brighten up anyone's day.

When Fern initially meets new people she tends to be a bit restless, but is always very loving towards everyone she meets. As she spends more time in her new environment she visibly relaxes, becoming much more confident and comfortable with her new people. Her fosters noticed that she became much more snuggly, enjoying napping on laps and spending time on the couch. She is also independent, often choosing to do her own thing if people aren't around to entertain her. Once she gets comfortable, she generally slows down and becomes very chill and low maintenance.That being said, Fern is not a couch potato! Her personality is a wonderful balance of playfulness and cuddliness and she lets both aspects of who she is shine through. She now loves to play with little balls and bounces around the house chasing them, all the while with her cute little ears flopping around.

Fern has been working on some basic training with her foster. She is currently completely house trained, crate trained, and walks well on the leash. She is also not a chewer or digger so far. Her only area for improvement is her barking. While she doesn't bark all the time, she does have some tendencies that are in the process of being addressed. She tends to bark at her reflection in the mirror and growls at cat videos on the TV :) She also sometimes barks for attention, which her fosters always correct with a firm "no".

Fern has also established a daily routine with her foster:
"Fern likes lazy mornings. She is in no rush to come out of her crate in the morning, sometimes deciding not to go downstairs with me at 8:00 but rather waiting for my husband to go down later around 9. She enjoys her breakfast and is happy to go on a walk right away or wait until later. She sleeps if we are busy and plays if we are willing to play. And she prefers to go to sleep by around 7 or 8, which is very early for our family, so she will often just go into another room to sleep on the couch, or come sleep on one of our laps until we take her up to bed. She goes into her crate with no fuss and sleeps through the night."

Fern was in the shelter with other dogs and initially on intake was with other dogs in our rescue. While out and about walking she generally ignores other dogs. She doesn't have a need to address them and clearly doesn't show any signs of distress. Fern is a great option to live by herself as she currently is or join a home that has an independent dog.

Fern has a subluxing patella. Right now it doesn't there isn't anything to be addressed. Some dogs live their entire life with it (most) and never require surgery. Some dogs later on do. It's common in small dogs. (It's where the knee pops out when running and causes the dog to skip) However, more than anything else, Fern needs a family that will give her all the love and attention she deserves and desires.

Fern is an option for a home that has had less experience. If there are children they need to be over the age of 8.

She is house and crate trained and has also had professional off leash training to get her started on the road to doing things right! There is a collar that goes with the off leash training and it works very well for her. She is a very happy and confident, loving girl. She adores children all ages and is wonderful playing with and meeting other dogs. She loves to play tug of war with a rope and is up for any fun games or adventures that you want her to go along with. We truly want her to have a fenced yard for her safety to play within. She is looking for someone who is active and can give her the attention and love that she deserves. She will give you her heart, soul and total committed future of being your "GIRL"! If you are interested please email us ASAP: This girl won't be hanging out long without someone seeing her beauty. Contact us via email only: ccrnewengland@gmail.com

animal.description:
All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, shots current (DHPP, Bordetella and Rabies where applicable), dewormed, flea and tick treated and microchipped.
* If you are interested in a dog, please first read the biography on the dog (keep scrolling down for the bio!) and then go to our website, www.dpsrescue.com for an application. Our adoption fee is $400-$800. Each biography will specifically list the adoption fee.Adoption Fee: $600
Betty is a 2 year old who weighs 9 lbs. She does shed. She came into our rescue very pregnant and had her puppies within days of arriving. This darling girl has been such a good mama to her pups, and now it's her turn to find her forever home! Betty came to us from a hoarding situation, where she and her ten siblings were left in a backyard, and thus emerged undersocialized. In her foster home, with love and patience, she has learned that people can be trusted. Once she trusts you, expect to be greeted in the morning with kisses and cuddles. When she is given a lot of time and space to feel comfortable, Betty is a super playful, goofy, sweet pup. This will take time and does not happen immediately.
Betty is looking for a family that will give her the time she needs to know she is safe. When she first arrived in her foster home, she was very skittish. Her foster family just let her develop trust on her own time and, as a result, Betty now allows them to pick her up, trim her nails, and give her pets. Developing trust happens by allowing her the first week to just adjust to the home. It doesn't mean forcing her to go on walks, forcing her to interact in any way with people. Rather in her foster home she had an xpen area and she stayed in there until she began to adjust. No one was constantly trying to pet her or touch her or force her to interact and so she formed trust much sooner than had the fosters tried to force interaction. By the end of the second week she was a completely different dog with them.
Betty wakes up around 8-9 AM, greets her puppies and has breakfast with them. Then she'll run around the house with the resident small dog, Squish. She likes to nap under the coffee table, in any tight corner of the house, her crate, or on a pile of toys. She follows her foster family around the house at a distance just to see what they're up to. Betty needs to be approached thoughtfully, as sometimes when spooked, she will run and hide. At night she has free roam of the house so she can take a potty break (she is potty pad trained) and come back to sleep in the bedroom.
Betty was very excited to stop nursing her puppies because she could then go outside on short walks around the neighborhood. Leash training is a work in progress, but she has improved a lot already. She tends to stay close to her foster family's feet or walk around them in circles. Betty is not afraid of the outside world at all! She's a brave girl. There is construction right outside her foster house now, and she doesn't seem to mind the noise or people who walk by.
Betty is a very skilled table surfer, and any food left on the table is hers if within reach. Her puppies taught her a bit about play, so eventually, she will likely enjoy some chew toys to play with, especially toys that have treats hiding inside. Betty is also a very good climber and escape artist, so doors will need to be shut and any holes under the fence will need to be patched up. Her foster family is currently working on keeping her calm whenever the front door opens so that she doesn't feel the need to bolt out. Betty likes to scavenge for trash in the garbage can (especially when bored), so all doors need to be kept closed at all times. She will bark if people come home or come downstairs just to alert the family, but responds well with verbal cues to be quiet.
Betty is a social butterfly with other dogs! She gets along incredibly well with one of the foster family's resident dogs. She cleans his face, climbs all over him when she sees him in the morning, and likes to eat out of the same food bowl as him. Having a friendly dog at home definitely helped her come out of her shell. On the other hand, the other dog is old and grumpy, so she knows to stay away from him - so respectful! Betty is also scared of the resident cat and wants nothing to do with her, which works out because the cat wants nothing to do with her!
With time, Betty makes for a wonderful, sweet companion. She just needs time and space.
Betty is only an option for a home that has had a dog in the last 5 years. If there is a resident dog who is confident that is a bonus. If there are children they need to be 12 and older and have grown up with dogs in their home (not just visiting other's dogs).

animal.description:
**WE ARE CURRENTLY DOING ADOPTIONS BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. YOU MUST CALL TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING. PLEASE LEAVE US A VOICEMAIL IF YOU ARE UNABLE TO REACH US. THANK YOU FOR YOUR PATIENCE AND UNDERSTANDING.- CCDP STAFF**

Hi there. My name is Claire. I'm about 5-6 years old and I weigh about 51 lbs. 
I was found in the East Liverpool area after a call was placed to the police department about hearing a dog barking in the woods. I was found tied in the middle of the woods with no food/water/shelter. There were no houses near by. 
I am a very timid girl, but very sweet once I get to know you. 
I get along with some but not all other dogs and should meet any other dogs I would live with in my new home, prior to adoption. 
If you're looking for a sweet dog to add to your family, please consider adopting me.

Our adoption fee is $150.00. The pound DOES NOT accept checks for adoption fees. We're able to accept cash for adoption OR Visa/ Mastercard/ Discover Card. A convenience fee of 2.39% will be applied to all credit/ debit card adoptions. If you intend to do a foster-to-adopt, the fee must be cash. ALL dogs/puppies adopted from our shelter will receive their parvo distemper vaccine, bordetella vaccine, rabies vaccine (if aged at 12 weeks or older), be dewormed with a 3 day course of panacur dewormer, be microchipped, receive their current Ohio dog license and will be spayed or neutered. ALL DOGS/PUPPIES WILL BE SPAYED OR NEUTERED unless a health issue prohibits the surgery from being performed. Not all dogs posted for adoption are spayed/ neutered yet. If you're driving a long distance to adopt, please verify that the vetting process has been completed and dog you're interested in adopting is still available for adoption. The above mentioned vetting is all included in your adoption fee. The adoption fee and what is included in the adoption fee is NON-NEGOTIABLE.

Adoptions MUST be done at the pound and in person as there is paperwork to fill out and an adoption contract that must be signed by the adopter. This means you must be willing to travel to our shelter to adopt.

IF the dog you're interested in adopting has medical conditions or injuries which require medical treatment, we ask that you help with the medical bills so we can continue to help the dogs coming in who need additional vet care.
We are a county run shelter, therefore we cannot control our intake or the health or behavior of the dogs that come in to our shelter.

Although we try our hardest to place all of our adoptable dogs, there are certain circumstances in which any dog in our care could be euthanized at any time and without further notice (IE: sudden untreatable medical condition or injury, temperament or behavioral problems which may not be apparent when the dog first arrives, lack or space, etc.), therefore all dogs at our shelter should be considered urgent. The adoption of a more highly adoptable dog will mean more time for the less adoptable dog in the kennel next to him!

Shelter hours are: Monday-Friday: 8 am- 4 pm
Saturday: 8 am - 11 am.
Sunday: 8 am - 11 am.
Adoptions are always welcome during hours of operation. We will make special arrangements for adoptions in advance.
There is nobody in the office on Saturday and Sunday, so therefore we are unable to answer or return phone calls over the weekend.

Can't adopt a dog? We would love to have more volunteers who are able to spend time with our dogs! The dogs LOVE going for walks and the socialization and exercise helps make the dogs more adoptable.

Contact information:
8455 County Home Road
Lisbon, OH 44432
(330)424-6663
Email: hpecorelli@ccclerk.org

animal.description:
Meet Riddick. This big boy just turned 6 years old on Christmas Day (his DOB is 12/25/2014) and he is looking for a new forever home. 
Riddick  was given up because his mom lost her job in Las Vegas and had to move to  California (she was able to get a job there) but her tiny apartment does not allow big dogs. 
Riddick was raised with cats and small dogs and does great with them, he is good with large breed female dogs as well.
Riddick was raised around children as well as does fine with them except he  does not like to be hugged, he has a very strong reaction to being hugged and we therefore think he should not go into a home with small children, older kids who would understand not to hug Riddick should be ok.
This boy is very sweet and well mannered and polite, he is housetrained and dog door trained as well. 
If you are interested in meeting Riddick please email Brenda at vegasdobes@aol.com to request an adoption application.    Please visit our web page at www.LVDDR.com to view our adoption requirements. There is an adoption fee of $400.00 required at the time of adoption.

animal.description:
Sophie- Female Pit/Beagle Mix  Color: Red & White 8 months old 31.6 lbs.
ID# D-40083

Sophie was found on the street and brought to the shelter for safety. She went unclaimed by her owner, even though we left messages that she was at the shelter. Sophie is ready to find a new home, where she will be loved and spoiled and have a family to spend time with, She is a wonderfully sweet and loving girl. She will need to be an inside dog with a secured fenced yard to have supervised play and exercise time in. She loves other dogs, loves play time, will need an active family, and needs some training. She's a fun girl. We believe she will be great with kids but a meet & greet is always needed. She does walk on a leash once you're able to get 1 on her, since she thinks that part is a fun game, and she is working on her housebreaking skills.

Sophie is current on basic vaccinations including Bordetella, been dewormed and is microchipped. She has tested Negative for Heartworms. 

Sophie is scheduled to be spayed on 2/4/21 and will receive her required Rabies vaccination at that time. She will need about a week to recover from her surgery before leaving to a new home. applications are being accepted..

For more information, please contact the City of Corsicana Animal Shelter at (903) 654-4928. The shelter is open Mon, Tues, Thurs and Fri from 12:00pm - 6:00pm and on Sat from 12:00pm - 4:00pm.

animal.description:
To apply to adopt, please go to www.adoptgoodkarma.com/adopting/ and fill out the online application. 

Lilly is 6.5 years old. Her owner recently passed away. She is 91 pounds. She can be shy at first but warms up quickly. She is spayed, heartworm negative, up to date on shots and preventatives. Due to her size we are recommending she be with kids 13 and older.

She is part of our foster to adopt program. The rescue will cover her getting vetted by our veterinarians during the foster period. If it is a love connection the foster gets first dibs to adopt. Please fill out an application if you are interested in fostering her. Typically the adoption fee is $300 but if you foster and decide to adopt we show our gratitude by providing a $50 discount plus her vetting.


Please do not send inquiries asking if animals are still available, if you see it online, that means it is.  We only post available animals.  In order to adopt one of our puppies or dogs, an application must be filled out prior to being invited to meet the dog.

DISCLAIMER:
Please note that these animals in most cases are abandoned and therefore breeds and sizes are our best estimates based on years of experience.  Many times we do not know the parents, so we are guessing.  If you are looking for a specific breed or size maybe rescue is not for you, it is very possible you will adopt a puppy we say will be medium size and the pup may be smaller than estimated or may be larger than estimated.  We do our best but many times we are wrong so please beware of this before rescuing from us.

animal.description:
**ADOPTION APPLICATION REQUIRED via our website Rarerescue.org**

ADOPTION FEES: Our Adoption Fees vary based on adoptability to help all of the animals in our organization. Please make sure to read the adoption fee below in the bio.

BREEDS: We are not breed experts. The breed(s) listed for each adoptable are best guesses or suggestions.

STEPS TO ADOPT:

Read the adoptable’s bio below, including their adoption fee

Read  ADOPTION PROCESS page under the "Adopt" section

Complete the  DOG ADOPTION APPLICATION (located on our website RARErescue.org)

*Applications will be attended to before general inquiries. We may or may not have time to respond to general inquiries if you have not submitted an application.

We understand that it is important to you to find the right fit for your family. We feel the same way! The application is important and necessary for this reason. 

All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered

*up to date on vaccines

*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)

*microchipped prior to adoption

BASIC INFORMATION:

Suggested Breed(s): Mountain Cur/Terrier mix

Gender: Male/Neutered

Approx. Age or D.O.B: 8/19/2020

Approx. Weight: 37 lbs

Coat Type: Short, Soft

Good around most dogs: Yes

Good around most cats: Not yet tested

Energy Level: Medium

Fence yard may be required: Yes

Any other specifics:  Check out this goofy boy! Ernie is a teen pup looking for love and adventure. He is in a foster home with other dogs and fenced yard and a doggy door. He is house trained and crate trained. Ernie would do best with a playful, well socialized dog. He also loves humans and loves to snuggle. A dog savvy person who's willing to continue basic training that Ernie has started will enjoy working with this intelligent boy. 

Will you be a Hero in Ernie's story?

Visit our website/Click on Adopt to APPLY today!  RARErescue.org

Adoption Fee: $185.00

PLEASE NOTE: We are a non-profit organization without municipal or government funding. Veterinary/Medical expenses are constant for an animal rescue. Our adoption fees not only help to provide vetting and care for the animal being adopted, but they also help to cover heartworm treatments and other treatable ailments that many animals, that would otherwise be euthanized, need in order to be made available for adoption.



Please understand that adopting an animal is a LIFETIME COMMITMENT to that animal and there will be veterinary expenses throughout their life that can often cost several hundreds, if not thousands of dollars (without pet insurance), especially without annual checkups and preventative care.  As a potential family for this pet you are responsible for their safety and that includes keeping them on your property.

***If you are not in the middle Tennessee area, transport can potentially be arranged to approved homes, depending on distance and local adaptability. We normally do not allow adoptions outside of 1.5 hours driving distance.

Thank you for choosing to adopt, foster, or aid in the rescue efforts of RARE!

animal.description:
Dobie 's owner surrendered him because of financial reasons but 3 days later felt she was shattered, got a job a new place and pleaded to get him back. We gave him back but only a short month later, he comes back to the rescue. The owner had a breakdown and has now been hospitalized and Dobie is a bit out of sorts. We knew before he needed to lose weight and has allergies. He did get allergy treatment but we are still noticing some scratching. It had been a month since he received the allergy injection so we gave him another and put him on medication and had his thyroid retested. He remains on thyroid medication as well as allergy medication. He does get a little food possessive, whenever food is around, towards other dogs and does seem to have some separation anxiety. He needs a home to keep up with his allergies and someone who is home more and will adhere to a diet to get him to lose the weight. He now needs a stable environment that will stick with him until the end. He is about 9-10 yrs of age. He is a happy guy and really loves his walks. He can go miles.

adoption fee is $200 Adoption fees go back to and cover all of the medical for all of the dogs. All dogs are spayed/neutered, vaccinated and micro chipped upon adoption and many have received further treatment for such things as lump removal, severe ear infections, leg injuries, etc..
For more information or to submit an adoption application, please visit our website at http://www.southernnevadabeaglerescue.com . We are also on Facebook at https://www.facebook.com/SouthernNevadaBeagleRescueFoundation . Come meet and play with our available dogs at Las Vegas area dog parks. Times and locations can be found at http://www.meetup.com/beagles-207/ . Contact us or check our Facebook updates ahead of time if you are interested in meeting a particular dog. All our dogs are in foster homes so not all are available to attend all our park meetups.
Our meetup group playdates allow you to socialize your beagle with his/her own breed at dog parks with large fenced areas where the beagles can run and play off-leash. Beagle enthusiasts, come bay with us..... AROOOOOOOOOOOO!

animal.description:
Star had a very sad life. She lived in a rabbit hutch and was solely used for breeding. Where she was, her life was only valued by how many puppies she could produce for profit. She spent 9 years in that box. When her owner passed, no one knew she was even back there. About 3-4 weeks later, a utility worker spotted her. By then her hay had so much urine and feces on it, that lime grew and she ended up with chemical burns. She had parasites and heartworms. She has been treated for all of that. She was transferred to us from our Mississippi partners. She recently had a veterinary evaluation to see if any medications could be adjusted or taken away. She was taken off of heart meds and we treated her for an ear infections. The doctor believes she is mostly deaf and blind. We have her scheduled for a badly needed dental and a fistula repair ( meaning there is a hole between her mouth and nose)Once that is done, she will be ready for a home. What Star needs is a forever home where she will be loved and kept safe and warm.

BUNKER

Cairn Terrier Mix |

Small (11-14 lbs.)

| Approximately 1 Year Old/ Neutered Male | Available for Adoption

animal.description:
Meet Riley!
Right now Riley is pretty shut-down and fearful. We have found he walks nicely on a leash and will warm up to new people fairly quickly, but is pretty timid. 
Riley cannot be in a home with cats and would require a meet and greet if you have a dog in the home. (We are still getting to know Riley, but he seemed pretty fearful of other dogs and needed space to be comfortable). 
Riley cannot be in a home with small children (or visiting grandchildren), no exceptions. He would be fine with children age 12 and up, but can and will be snappy with small children who get into his space.
He is house trained and crate trained and would make an ideal pet for a family with a quiet home and who are willing to allow him time to settle in and get comfortable.

Meet baby girl Athena. Athena was born around September 2020 and is ready for a furever home! 

Part of the fun of adopting a puppy from an animal rescue is the surprise that comes along with their growth. Their size at adulthood is simply a guess and cannot be guaranteed. When you adopt a puppy from GPG, we trust that you will love and care for this animal regardless of their actual adult size and physical appearance.

If you're interested in meeting Athena, please visit our website to learn about our adoption process and to fill out an application, www.gatewaypets.org/adopt

All of our dogs and cats will be micro-chipped, spayed or neutered, and up-to-date on vaccinations at the time of adoption. 

For more photos of Athena, follow us on Facebook Gateway Pet Guardians and Instagram @gatewaypets ... #gpgAthena. 

To view other adoptable pets from our shelter, please visit, www.gatewaypets.org/adopt
Gateway Pet Guardians is proud to offer a variety of mixed breed dogs available for adoption. However, please keep in mind that we rarely know the genetic background of the animals we rescue and, as such, we cannot guarantee the exact breed combinations found within this dog. However, we do not know his/her actual genetic makeup. Just know that this dog is probably a variety of several different breeds that have combined to create one very amazing and unique animal.

animal.description: Hi, my name is CHICKADEE and I would love to meet you. I am a Spayed Female Pit Bull Terrier. The shelter staff think I am about 1 years and 0 months old. I have been at the shelter since Oct 16, 2020. Meet Chickadee! This pocket pittie is slowly gaining her confidence in a loving foster home. She has had a rough start in life, and she is looking for a family who is willing to give her a steady routine, as familiarity is where she finds safety and success. She would like a quiet adult-only household with shy/fearful dog experience, who will go to the moon and back for her. Chickadee likes to be told what is a happening and when, as she is very unsure about most things in life, and communication helps her understand. She may do well with a friendly pup in the home - a pup that is able to read her body language and give her the space she needs. She just needs to learn the joys of a warm bed, and a loving home. For more information about Chickadee, please email adoptions@thehumanesociety.org

animal.description:
PLEASE READ COMPLETE BIO BEFORE APPLYING. PLEASE DO NOT INQUIRE OR APPLY UNLESS YOU MEET ALL THE CRITERIA LISTED BELOW. DUE TO THE AMOUNT OF APPS/INQUIRED WE RECEIVE, WE WILL NOT RESPOND TO APPS/INQUIRES THAT DO NOT MEET THE CRITERIA FOR THIS DOG. Thank you! 

Meet Alba!

Alba is a pocket pittie at approximately 40 lbs and around 2 years old.  She is spayed,  up to date on vaccines and microchipped.  Poor girl was found as a stray with a large open head wound seeping with infection, fractured skull, and very skinny.  Her wound is a distant memory to her now as it’s just the last of the scabs healing now.  She has already gained over 10 lbs and looking and feeling great!  She would do best with dogs her size and bigger as she likes to be a bit bossy and play rough with her dog friends.  She is a dominant female who would do best with male dogs or submissive females that don’t mind her being the more dominant one.  She is crate and house trained.  She needs help with her manners like jumping and mouthing, she is making improvements on it but will need an adopter to continue with that as well.  Because she is still working on her manners we recommend kids 10 and up.  Cats are unknown but we can cat test her if needed.

Adoption fee is $250.00. 
Adoption application & home visit required.  Alba requires a fenced in yard. Adopters must live within 30 miles of Cleveland. 

If interested in Alba fill out an app on our website www.muttsinarutrescue.com

animal.description:
Xena is an 8 month old, 60lb Staffordshire terrier/ Boxer Mix

Xena is currently located in South Texas and will be transported to the Pacific Northwest.

Hi! I have so many names! And I know them all! Officially my name is Xena Princess Warrior Wiggle Butt, but you can call me Xena for short, and also wiggle butt, and wiggle. My best quality is eternal happiness- I have never been sad, well until anyone leaves the room. I don’t know what they are doing but I have followed my humans back and forth ten times! I’m not perfect- I like to collect things- but I don’t chew them up, I just bring them to my human. Ok I am naughty cause I like the way toilet paper feels when I pull it apart- that’s why they call me naughty, Whatever that means. But they say naughty and then they say pankin and I tuck my ears and chase my tail- but I don’t know what that means- I just like to act like nothing is wrong so I act cute. It works every time. I almost forgot! I have a windmill tail! It’s shaped like an S and when I wag it I create energy like a windmill and my butt wiggles SO SO much! My humans look at me and wiggle and I wiggle back. If they say wiggle wiggle wiggle I go crazy! I love the sound of kisses so when I play I make that sound when I grab my toys. I want to sleep in your bed and if you let me I will sit on your lap!

Our organization only adopts within the United States.

Faith and Hope is a multi-state rescue with locations in Texas, Washington and Oregon. All dogs are rescued from the state of Texas to and transported to our Washington and Oregon locations with placement in their adoptive families. Our $475 adoption fee includes all core vaccinations 
DHPP, rabies, spay/neuter, microchip)

If interested in learning more, please email us at faithandhopeadoptions@gmail.com or fill out our online application.

https://www.faithandhopefoundation.org/adoptionapp

If interested in learning more about our adoptable dogs and adoption process, or our foster home program, please contact us at above email.

Due to the number of requests that we receive on our puppies and dogs, please be advised that all adoption applications are processed in the order received. Once we send you an application, your place in line does not get reserved until your application is returned to us.

animal.description:
My name is "Tiger" but don't be fooled by my name, I'm a very sweet little lady! I just arrived in New Hampshire from a crowded southern shelter and can't wait to experience a wonderful life with you!

I'm a petite, 3 year old black brindle with the most beautiful brown eyes. I weigh 47 lbs., am spayed and current on vaccinations. I can be a tad bit shy at first but I quickly warm up to really nice people. I'm a happy girl who loves to walk (although, the cold weather up here will take some getting used to for me!). I'm finding toys to be really fun as well! What I want the most is your affection. I really want to be your best friend and I promise to shower you with kisses and wiggles!

I will need to meet any potential canine siblings to ensure compatibility. Children ages 10 older would be best and I need a cat-free home. 

We kindly ask, if you have questions regarding Tiger, PLEASE EMAIL:

adoption@popememorialcvhs.org

*************************************************

How To Adopt a Pet

We are currently offering adoptions by appointment only, due to the Coronavirus. The Adoption Center remains closed to drop-in visitors.

The process to schedule an appointment begins with the submission of an application, which can be found on our website. Once the application is approved, we will reach out to you to schedule an appointment. Please bear with us, the new process has slowed our response time.

If you do not see an animal that would fit into your home, we highly recommend checking our website weekly as new animals may become available. We do not offer a waitlist for specific breeds, types, etc. 

As always, adoptions are first come, first serve, meaning the applicant who is approved first gets their choice of available appointment times and thus his/her choice of animals to meet and adopt. We are not able to extend holds on any animals at this time, so we ask interested adopters to make their adoption decision during their appointment and be prepared to take their new pet home with you.

The easiest way to communicate with us with any questions is via email to: 

adoption@popememorialcvhs.org


No phone calls please - Submit an application here ----> 

https://popememorialcvhs.org/adoption-application


.
.
.
.
.
. Primary Color: Black Brindle Secondary Color: White Weight: 47lbs Age: 3yrs 0mths 1wks Animal has been Spayed

animal.description: Hi, I'm Harold. I had a bit of a rough start to life. I had to share a house with way too many dogs and I never really learned what love from a human was. That is until the great people at Texas Humane Heroes took me in. I have spent lots of time with the ladies here and I am slowly learning to love people. At first, I didn't know what a leash was. It SCARED me! I can still be nervous when I get leashed up but I also know that means I am going to go for a walk which is something I have learned to love as well. Come spend some time with me and see if I would be a good fit for you. I think I like other dogs but they would need to be calm. I am not sure about kids yet. It would probably be best if I was in a home with older teens and adults only. I appreciate you coming to take a look at me.

animal.description:
Weight: 42 lbs.

Adoption Price: $100

WANT TO TAKE ME HOME TODAY? SCHEDULE AND ADOPTION APPOINTMENT.
To Schedule An Adoption Appointment:
1. Fill out and submit our online Adoption Application.
2. Please only submit ONE Adoption Application. (Our Application is for general pre-approval, not for a specific adoptable animal).
3. Once received, the Allen County SPCA will review your application. Applications are reviewed in the order they are received.
4. We will contact you to let you know your Adoption Status and schedule an Adoption Appointment. Applications may take up to 1-2 days to process. Please give us a call at the shelter at 260-744-0454 if you have not heard back from us within 48 hours.
5. If you haven't found your perfect match at the shelter, that's okay too - pre-approved applications are valid for 6 months!

Come prepared! Please bring proof of a current rabies vaccine for all pets living in the home. If you have another dog, you are welcome to bring him or her with you so that we can safely perform a dog interaction.

Unfortunately, animals cannot be held for you.

A Special Note from the Allen County SPCA:
Remember, pets are a lifelong commitment. We at the Allen County SPCA ask that you take adding a furry family member to your home seriously, and do your research on the different breeds before adopting. We also ask that you are able to keep up on yearly vaccinations, monthly preventatives, a good diet, daily exercise, training, and most of all, LOVE. If you ever have an issue with a pet that you adopted, please contact us right away; we may be able to help, or we can put you in touch with someone who can. All set? Come in and adopt today!

Mallory was found on 1/29/21 at Highway 99 and Highway 36. It is unknown at this time if she is spayed. 

If you believe this is your missing dog, please contact the shelter at (541) 689-1503. Since this dog is new to the shelter and we are still looking for their family, they are not viewable on the adoption floor at this time.

Our shelter software requires that we choose a primary breed for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs can be unreliable and for most dogs we are only guessing at their primary breed. animal.description:
Meet Lea, a 10 month old doberman/husky mix who is in need of a new home. She will be spayed, and is already up to date on vaccinations, dewormed & micrchipped. 

Lea has lived her whole life outside on a chain with a dog house to shield her from the elements, but her owner recognized that is not enough and turned her over to us to find a better home. She will require a fully fenced in yard, and an active family. 

She is good with kids, had no reaction to the lazy cat in the foster home and is learning to trust people. She has also met 3 dogs individually, and done considerably well. Her foster will continue to allow her supervised play time with their personal dogs to socialize her. She is also learning what living indoors is like. She is working on leash skills, and crate training, as well as potty training. If you think Lea would be a good addition to your family, please apply at thepitbullpen.org

animal.description:
**This is a courtesy post for Australian Shepherds Furever Rescue. Please see further in the bio for adoption instructions**

Sweet Delilah, an Aussie/cattle dog mix, is looking for a family who will love and cherish her. Through unfortunate circumstances, she has had 4 homes in the past 4 years, including time at a city shelter. That hasn’t stopped her from loving and trusting people, however, as she adores her humans. We’re told she’s around 10 years, but you’d never know it by her energy level and love of playing.  

Delilah’s foster mom says she loves to play fetch and run in the yard. She loves squeaky toys, especially her squeaky pig. She enjoys going on walks and likes to explore. She hasn’t met a stranger and is excited to see people on walks. Sometimes she’s a little too excited and wants to jump on people but stops when reminded about all 4 on the floor. She loves to be near her person but isn’t anxious or needy about it. She also loves soft things, like chairs, couches, beds, and her memory foam dog bed. When her foster parents are tired from playing, Delilah sometimes makes her own fun by chasing her tail. She’s only actually caught it once, then looked at foster mom as if to say, “what is this?”  

She knows her basic commands and is happy to show you “sit”, “stay”, “paw”, and “down”. Her foster family says she can be trusted out in the house when they’re gone, and they haven’t had to crate her. She is completely housetrained.  

Delilah will be an excellent companion for someone who can give her all the love and attention. She needs to be the only dog in the home and cannot live with cats. She was not given proper opportunity to exercise in her prior home, so she’s been working on getting back to a better weight and has made great progress. She’s working on losing another 10-15 pounds (currently 68) and will need her family’s help to do this. After the first few days in her foster home, realizing there was no 24-hour all-you-can-eat buffet, she’s settled into and really enjoys her exercise routine.  

Delilah has been given a clean bill of health from our vet. She is up to date on all vaccines, spayed, microchipped and heartworm negative. She is on monthly heartworm, flea and tick preventatives.  

Delilah is being fostered in the St. Louis, MO area. If you’d like more information or are interested in meeting her, please fill out an application here… http://www.australianshepherdsfurever.org/adoption…

Meet Gunner, the sweetest boy ever!!  Gunner was found as a stray near the Oklahoma border.  He was a skeleton when he was found.  Fast forward 3 weeks and he is now at a healthy weight!

We will contact you for a meet and greet!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact DDJ for more information about this pet.Thanks for your interest in a pet from A.R.F.! If you see a pet here, they are still available for adoption and you should apply through our adoption application on our website at https://www.arf-il.org/adopt/application/
Naveen is a 13 week old male Shepherd mix who weighs in at 23 pounds. His siblings are Aladdin, Elsa and Merida. Naveen is the typical puppy - he loves to play, cuddle, and give kisses. He has lots of energy and is working on house training.

This pup is micro-chipped and up to date on all vaccinations, neutered. The new family will be required to complete a basic obedience course of their choosing. The pup's adoption fee is $375. Please note ARF does not approve applications for any puppy under 6 months of age to families that live outside of Illinois and/or beyond 100 miles of Wheaton or Glen Ellyn, IL. A meeting will not be scheduled until you have an approved application, so if you're interested in adopting this pup fill out an online application today! https://www.arf-il.org/adopt/application/ Once your application has been approved, an ARF volunteer will contact you to arrange a meeting. ARF is an all volunteer organization. Due to a high volume of applications, we are often unable to respond to questions until your application has been approved. Thank you for your patience!

Thank you for considering a rescue pet from A.R.F.-Animal Rescue Foundation! We are
based in Wheaton, IL and conduct adoption events in the DuPage County area. If you are interested in adopting one of our pets, please submit an adoption application at https://www.arf-il.org/adopt/application/

Adoption appointments are scheduled based on the order of applications received, so submit your application early! Submitting an application does not commit you to any animal but does get you a head start with the adoption approval process. Due to a high volume of applications, we are often unable to respond to questions or schedule meetings until your application has been approved. More information about our adoption process can be found on our website here: https://www.arf-il.org/adopt/

As an all-volunteer, foster home-based organization, A.R.F. Animal Rescue Foundation does not have a facility where applicants can visit our animals. Please visit https://www.arf-il.org/events/ for a list of our upcoming adoption events.

Thank you for choosing to adopt, not shop!

Apply to adopt by clicking on the link below

http://www.wagsandwhiskerspetrescue.com/adopt.html

Thank you so much for looking into wags and whiskers for your next family member.

All of our pets are up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, heartworm tested if over 6 months old and will be spayed or neutered before being allowed to go home.

Unfortunately, we don't always know the background of each dog. Some were dumped, abandoned in an empty house, left tied to a tree, picked up by animal control as strays, or simply unwanted by their owners. Please take into consideration that owning a pet is a 10+ year commitment and discuss with all members of your family before submitting an application to adopt.

If you have already filled out an online adoption application with our organization in the last 6 months you do not need to fill out another application. Please call or email us to schedule an appointment. 530-895-8888

If you are interested in meeting this pet please apply to adopt at
